larger brands in the Mattels of the world, companies like Black & Decker an=
d some of the ones I mentioned like Zulily, they=E2=80=99re going to want u=
s to integrate with their existing infrastructure. And so Shopify has alway=
s been really good on the API side of ensuring that you can get exactly wha=
t you want from us, whether it=E2=80=99s directly from our core product or =
it=E2=80=99s by leveraging some of our partners. But that=E2=80=99s somethi=
ng that we=E2=80=99re really proud of. And that=E2=80=99s sort of on the pr=
oduct-enhancing side.

This is definitely a bit of a non-answer answer, which I think is the answe=
r: the existential question of =E2=80=9CBuy with Prime=E2=80=9D is now more=
 pressing than ever. One reader wrote me to argue that Amazon ought to seiz=
e this moment to build a true Shopify alternative once-and-for-all, and whi=
le I see the strategic allure, I do think there is a reason why Amazon got =
out of that business in the first place. From a 2021 profile of Lutke in Bl=
oomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2021-12-23/shopify-amazon=
-retail-rivalry-heats-up-with-covid-sparked-online-shopping-booma ) :

An even more critical event came a few months after the IPO. Amazon also op=
erated a service that let independent merchants run their websites, called =
Webstore. Bang & Olufsen, Fruit of the Loom, and Lacoste were among the 80,=
000 or so companies that used it to run their online shops. If he wanted to=
, Bezos surely had the resources and engineering prowess to crush Shopify a=
nd steal its momentum.

But Amazon execs from that time admit that the Webstore service wasn=E2=80=
=99t very good, and its sales were dwarfed by all the rich opportunities th=
e company was seeing in its global marketplace, where customers shop on Ama=
zon.com, not on merchant websites. At the time, the company was also develo=
ping house brands such as Amazon Basics, and Webstore sellers had to get co=
mfortable with the possibility that the tech giant might see their success =
and knock off their best products. It was a =E2=80=9Cfox-in-the-henhouse pr=
oblem. Merchants were sleeping with one eye open,=E2=80=9D says a former Am=
azon executive who worked on Webstore, who spoke on condition of anonymity =
because he wasn=E2=80=99t authorized to speak publicly about the issue.

In late 2015, in one of Bezos=E2=80=99 periodic purges of underachieving bu=
sinesses, he agreed to close Webstore. Then, in a rare strategic mistake th=
at=E2=80=99s likely to go down in the annals of corporate blunders, Amazon =
sent its customers to Shopify and proclaimed publicly that the Canadian com=
pany was its preferred partner for the Webstore diaspora. In exchange, Shop=
ify agreed to offer Amazon Pay to its merchants and let them easily list th=
eir products on Amazon=E2=80=99s marketplace. Shopify also paid Amazon $1 m=
illion =E2=80=94 a financial arrangement that=E2=80=99s never been previous=
ly reported.

Bezos and his colleagues believed that supporting small retailers and their=
 online shops was never going to be a large, profitable business. They were=
 wrong =E2=80=94 small online retailers generated about $153 billion in sal=
es in 2020, according to AMI Partners. =E2=80=9CShopify made us look like f=
ools,=E2=80=9D says the former Amazon executive.

I=E2=80=99m not sure I agree; Amazon, particularly then, was an e-commerce =
Aggregator: their model was predicated on being the place consumers went to=
 buy by default, which gave them power over suppliers, which they leveraged=
 into an expansion of their much higher-margin marketplace business. And, i=
n this view, building out a private label business made a lot of sense.

Things might be different today, though; I wrote in Beyond Aggregation: Ama=
zon as a Service ( https://stratechery.com/2022/beyond-aggregation-amazon-a=
s-a-service/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnB=
hc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9yd=
C5vbmxpbmUiLCJlbnQiOnsidXJpIjpbImh0dHBzOi8vc3RyYXRlY2hlcnkuY29tLzIwMjIvYmV5=
b25kLWFnZ3JlZ2F0aW9uLWFtYXpvbi1hcy1hLXNlcnZpY2UvIl19LCJleHAiOjE2ODYxNDQ3OTc=
sImlhdCI6MTY4MzU1Mjc5NywiaXNzIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9zdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbm=
xpbmUvb2F1dGgiLCJzY29wZSI6ImZlZWQ6cmVhZCBhcnRpY2xlOnJlYWQgYXNzZXQ6cmVhZCBjY=
XRlZ29yeTpyZWFkIiwic3ViIjoiUnNldVlFOGpnSGVQcFdKZjFmQWI0QyIsInVzZSI6ImFjY2Vz=
cyJ9.PaMuvvKhVGSlPEkgv1lzkf8l1Pk7SX8CdungrAfLZsYHlBoWGlCf9ccOTqsU92ArnDoNYr=
udNYKSfl6lag0D3YVmYjJzVccnnoFXb7vfHwYob8lVBQRbLEuzrmsbQYBYFpAkIjR0p_bUv0V4y=
3beJ1yMf6zsPnYGyggXLq0uOmUuEV2pQGPFB9zaF0dAK3prI7VCp9C5TrNEWlCI9g3rHHZq_PkF=
SGHoVF1-R8sK944TNktPdtRgFzt1oYpv-O8tSIWK0BzMVRcrG5yd7GVqDZLQG0sF38M5qPiylzu=
GNJ5pRFkn2564BVp3MlTc6scuD2OGnBkq4653R8v8Ej2yqg ) that =E2=80=9CBuy with Pr=
ime=E2=80=9D seemed to represent a shift in strategy beyond Aggregation to =
logistics-as-a-service.

Amazon=E2=80=99s control of demand has been =E2=80=94 and will continue to =
be =E2=80=94 a tremendous advantage; Amazon not only has power over its sup=
pliers, but it also gets all of the relevant data from consumers, which it =
can feed into a self-contained ad platform that is untouched by regulation =
from either governments or Apple.

At the same time, limiting a business to customer touchpoints that you cont=
rol means limiting your overall addressable market. This may not matter in =
markets where there are network effects (which means you appeal to everyone=
) and you are an Aggregator dealing with zero marginal costs (and thus can =
realistically cover every consumer); in the case of e-commerce, though, Ama=
zon will never be the only option, particularly given The Anti-Amazon Allia=
nce working hard to reach consumers=E2=80=A6

This shift would make the rest of Amazon=E2=80=99s business look more like =
AWS; I concluded:

I think it=E2=80=99s meaningful that =E2=80=9CBuy With Prime=E2=80=9D is th=
e first major initiative of new CEO Andy Jassy=E2=80=99s regime; I don=E2=
=80=99t think it=E2=80=99s an accident that it is so clearly inspired by AW=
S. AWS=E2=80=99s strength is its focus on infrastructure at scale; successf=
ully moving e-commerce beyond aggregation to the same type of service busin=
ess model would put his stamp on the company in a meaningful way, and, cont=
ra that quote in Bloomberg Businessweek, mark Jassy as nobody=E2=80=99s foo=
l.

To return to Shopify, if the company believes that their main quest is buil=
ding out storefronts and incorporating AI and whatever else, and that thing=
s like logistics are side quests best handled by focused partners, then it=
=E2=80=99s pretty hard to justify not supporting Buy with Prime for any rea=
son other than bare-knuckled self interest =E2=80=94 and from my perspectiv=
e that=E2=80=99s understandable! That story, though, is a much harder sell =
for Shopify=E2=80=99s merchants, who could previously be mollified by the f=
act that Shopify was spending serious money on building out their own logis=
tics alternative.

Shopify does have other levers to pull: Shopify Audiences, the ad product I=
 called for, appears to be doing quite well, both in terms of driving merch=
ant business and also in driving upgrades to Shopify Plus; being a part of =
Shopify Audiences depends on being a part of Shopify Payments, which means =
to the extent Shopify Audiences becomes essential for merchants is the exte=
nt to which Buy with Prime isn=E2=80=99t even an alternative.

Indeed, maybe that gets at where there is a potential for an agreement betw=
een Shopify and Amazon: from Amazon=E2=80=99s perspective the data from bei=
ng the payment provider would certainly be nice to have, particularly if it=
 can be tied back into the consumer-facing business; if Amazon really is me=
aningfully shifting beyond Aggregation, though, then there is value in havi=
ng Shopify merchants using its logistics even without payments. And, just l=
ike before, Shopify could sweeten the deal, perhaps by cutting Amazon in on=
 some of its payment margins (slight though they may be).

This would be a win for both sides: Shopify=E2=80=99s merchants could use B=
uy with Prime, Amazon could get the extra volume (and merchant fees) and a =
bit of margin (and besides, ATT makes third-party data less valuable anyway=
s), and Shopify could well and truly focus on its main quest without having=
 to find out whether the logistics side quest was in fact an essential defe=
nse against an opponent that could upend the board completely.

